{"key":"processedPost-12784475","value":{"id":12784475,"first":12784038,"last":12784475,"when":1277232566,"utime":"06/22/10 09:49 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>iFung said:</b><br />If the lowest setting on my oven is 150, can I put my pot of water/substrate in there at 150 for a while to pasteurize it instead of manually trying to keep it in range on the stove top?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />It might take ten to fifteen hours in the oven at 150F for the water and substrate to reach that temperature, since air is such a crappy heat transfer medium.&nbsp; <br /><br />Or, a few minutes on a stove top.<br /><br />Look at it this way:&nbsp; It takes 90 minutes with the oven turned up to 350F for a small chicken to reach 170F, which is when a chicken is considered cooked.&nbsp; I'm assuming your pot of water is much larger than a chicken.&nbsp; You'll be far better off to stick to tried and true pasteurization methods.&nbsp; You want to heat your substrates rapidly to 140F and then keep them there for an hour to 90 minutes, and then cool them off to use.&nbsp; This process would take many hours in the oven, screwing up the pasteurization.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pasteurizing in the Oven?"}}